A single America, two classes of citizens
New York — as I write this article, officials across the United States are still counting the votes in the 2020 presidential election.
Once the results are finalized, recounts and legal challenges are sure to follow.
This is to be expected in this highly competitive election with record voter turnout.
Only American citizens can vote for the President of the United States, but this choice affects people everywhere.
If determining the election results is still too early, discussing the implications of this election for the world's most powerful country is not too early.
From a positive perspective, the United States remains a strong democratic country.
Despite practical limitations related to the pandemic, voter participation remains high.
This process seems to be proceeding as planned.
And violent incidents are rare.
The court is investigating decisions by the U.S. Postal Service that appear to be politically motivated, hindering the delivery of ballots from areas where votes are expected to mainly come from Democrats.
Current U.S. President Trump announced his victory without any basis on Tuesday night, and his demand to stop counting votes (at least in states where he was leading) seemed to be ignored.
However, it is concerning that the division among American voters remains significant.
The votes of the two candidates are almost equal.
It is no surprise that this division is likely to lead to a split in government.
If the current trend continues, the Democratic Party will win the White House and continue to control the House of Representatives, while the Republican Party will continue to control the Senate.
Governorships and state legislative seats are almost evenly split between the two parties (with the Republicans having a slight advantage).
The Democratic Party's expected "blue wave" did not materialize.
Biden is likely to win the popular vote by a significant margin, probably securing around four to five million votes out of nearly 160 million.
However, Republicans held on to many seats that were predicted to flip, while the Democrats actually lost seats in the House of Representatives.
This outcome does not come from strong authorization, nor does it stem from political adjustments.
Trump's poll numbers are very strong, with 5 million more votes than in 2016, making him the second-highest vote-getter in U.S. presidential history and surpassing all previous winners.
Particularly noteworthy is that this occurred against the backdrop of record-high daily new coronavirus cases and over 1,000 deaths.
Just as its government's mishandling of the pandemic's consequences became most severe, nearly half of the voters turned to support him.
Even if Trump loses, which seems likely, he will still have strong influence, especially if he continues to remain in the public eye (which also seems likely).
Even if he himself does not run, he is likely to have a significant influence on the selection of the Republican nominee in the 2024 presidential election.
The Republican Party will be very different from the party of former Presidents George W. Bush or Ronald Reagan.
Trumpism — a modern American populism — will still be a powerful force.
Not surprisingly, despite having no evidence to support his claims, Trump continues to try to portray himself as noble and upright, attempting to undermine the legitimacy of the election results and accusing there being fraudulent voting.
Many of his supporters will refuse to accept the legitimacy of Biden's presidency.
Trump is very likely to never give up and will certainly not attend the inauguration ceremony of his successor.
As Will Rogers once said, Trump has never encountered a rule he couldn't break.
Americans are increasingly living in different worlds.
They categorize themselves into different communities and regions based on shared viewpoints.
And each world tends to watch its own cable TV channels, listen to its own radio stations and podcasts, and visit its own websites.
Meanwhile, the absence of a national citizenship curriculum has facilitated the differentiation among people from different generations.
It is worth emphasizing that national division is not usually along economic lines.
People from all social strata voted for both candidates, and the voting patterns by population, gender, and race are not as one-sided as many predicted.
They mainly differ in terms of remedies.
Education level is clearly an indicator of political orientation, as is geographical location. Republican voters tend to live in suburban and rural areas, while Democratic voters tend to live in metropolitan regions.
However, the role of culture in American politics may be greater than any other factor.
In fact, foreign policy seems not to be very important in campaigns, except for mobilizing specific districts, such as large Cuban and Venezuelan communities in South Florida.
Against this backdrop, it is difficult to gain public support for major reforms to the way presidential elections or government operations are conducted.
This situation is similar to that of reforming the United Nations Security Council.
Many people believe that the current system has serious flaws and lacks representativeness, but it is impossible to reach a consensus on reform because any potential solution would benefit some people and harm others.
It is not surprising that those who would suffer losses from the changes will resist them.
This will make governance difficult.
This largely depends on Mitch McConnell, the Republican Senate leader, and his ability and willingness to cooperate with the future Biden administration.
Collaboration will also require Biden to make compromises, which is sure to be resisted by members of his party with strong ideological leanings.
Democrats have tried to dismiss everything that Trump and his representatives stand for in a sharp manner.
But they were not successful.
While Republicans sought an election that would recognize Trump.
But this also did not go as they hoped.
Instead, the election revealed a nation and two classes of citizens.
They will have to coexist; but whether they can coexist remains to be seen.
